<![CDATA[
<img class="wp-image-2757903 size-full" src="http://images.indianexpress.com/2016/04/murli-vijay-m.jpg" alt="KXIP vs RPS, RPS vs KXIP, KXIP RPS, RPS KXIP, Punjab vs Pune, Pune vs Punjab, IPL 2016, IPL, IPL KXIP vs RPS, MS Dhoni, Faf du Plessis, M Vijay, Murli, Vohra, Maxwell, Glenn Maxwell, Cricket" /> Murali Vijay hit 53 off 49 balls with five fours and two huge sixes. (Source: BCCI/IPL) <p><em><strong>Synopsis:</strong> M, S Sharma contain MS <a href="http://indianexpress.com/tag/ms-dhoni/">Dhoni</a> &amp; Co despite Du Plessis Smith effort. Maxwell wakes up on right side after Vijay-Vohra opening act to take the home team home.</em></p> <p><strong>M, S Sharma show</strong></p> <p>Sandeep Sharma was a bright spot for the Kings XI Punjab in their otherwise unimpressive start to the season, which began with two losses. Against Rising Pune SuperGiants, he again provided the early spark.</p> <p>The first over saw Sandeep swing the ball appreciably, and a close lbw appeal foreshadowed what was in store for Dhoni&#8217;s team. Off the first ball of his second over, he sent back the in-form Ajinkya Rahane, who edged the ball onto his stumps in an attempt to hit out after a subdued start. Apart from this wicket, Sandeep went on to bowl 10 dot balls in his three overs in the power play. He would return to bowl the 11th over and remove Thisara Perera. But Sandeep was not the only Sharma troubling Pune. Former Chennai Super Kings bowler, Mohit Sharma, too added to Dhoni&#8217;s woes, bowling with great control. While Kylie Abbot was targeted by Steve Smith and Faf du Plessis in the later stage of the match, Mohit bowled a mix of good length and yorker balls apart from an occasional bouncer. It seemed Mohit just knew what balls to bowl to his former teammates, du Plessis and Dhoni, and both fell to him in the final over. It was largely due to Sandeep and Mohit&#8217;s efforts that Pune were restricted to a well below-par 152 for four.</p> <p><strong>PHOTOS: <a href="http://indianexpress.com/photos/sports-gallery/ipl-2016-rps-vs-kxip-openers-power-kxip-to-first-win-over-pune-2757881/">Match recap in pictures</a></strong></p> <p><strong>Opening act</strong></p> <p>Pune needed early wicket, but Punjab&#8217;s openers Manan Vohra and Murali Vijay had other ideas. Last IPL, Vohra played only seven matches. This season, he has surpassed his previous year&#8217;s aggregate despite playing only three matches so far. Vohra and Vijay, who had a string of low scores, kept up the pace with the required run rate. Both raised their half-centuries and their 97-run stand in 12.2 overs put the home team on course. But that&#8217;s when Pune&#8217;s spinners hit back.</p> <p><strong>Maxwell wakes up</strong></p> <p>Leg-spinner Murugan Ashwin took three wickets, including that of Vijay, and left-arm spinner Ankit Sharma accounted for Vohra as Punjab appeared to have blown it away, with 35 needed off last four overs – two of which were to be bowled by the two Ashwins. Glenn Maxwell poor form inspired little confidence. However, the destructive Australian woke up on the right side today and smoked a six and a four off the leggie and then subjected his more illustrious namesake to the same treatment to take the home team home in the 19th over.</p> <p><strong>Brief Scores:</strong> Rising Pune Supergiants 152/7 in 20 overs (Faf Du Plessis 67 off 53b, Steve Smith 38 off 26b, Mohit Sharma 3/23) lost to Kings XI Punjab 153/4 (Murali Vijay 53 off 49b, Manan Vohra 51 off 33b, Maxwell 32 not out off 14b, M Ashwin 3/36) in 18.4 overs by six wickets.</p><img alt="" border="0" src="http://pixel.wp.com/b.gif?host=indianexpress.com&#038;blog=53855017&#038;post=2757896&#038;subd=indianexpressonline&#038;ref=&#038;feed=1" width="1" height="1" />
